## Steps to Reproduce

You can reproduce by running the following example on an iOS physical device:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  // This widget is the root of your application.
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Flutter dictation issue',
      home: MyHomePage(),
    );
  }
}

class MyHomePage extends StatefulWidget {
  MyHomePage({
    Key key,
  }) : super(key: key);

  @override
  _MyHomePageState createState() => _MyHomePageState();
}

class _MyHomePageState extends State<MyHomePage> {
  TextEditingController _controller = TextEditingController();

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(),
      body: Center(
        child: TextField(
          controller: _controller,
          onChanged: (value) {
            print('onChanged :$value');
          },
        ),
      ),
      floatingActionButton: FloatingActionButton(
        onPressed: () {
          print('clear');
          _controller.clear();
        },
        child: Icon(Icons.clear),
      ),
    );
  }
}

```

Just tap the dictation button, say something, then tap the floating action button that should clear the text field:

<img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/34095172/121653327-df993200-ca9c-11eb-95c3-d54b892ce985.png" width="200">

<img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/34095172/121653868-6c43f000-ca9d-11eb-8c15-1d70f977632d.png" width="200">

**Expected results:**
The textfield text is erased.

**Actual results:** 
The text still appears on the textfield after calling `clear()` on the controller. The textfield `onChanged` method is triggered after the clear :

print output :
```
flutter: onChanged :H
flutter: onChanged :He
flutter: onChanged :Hel
flutter: onChanged :Hell
flutter: onChanged :Hello
flutter: clear
flutter: onChanged :Hello
```

comments:
+1 also having this issue. Tapping my send button (which calls `controller.clear()`) in my application while the keyboard is still in dictation mode causes the controller's text to remain there. Works fine when not using dictation.

As a workaround, I did this:
```dart
_messageCtrl.clear();
Future.delayed(Duration(milliseconds: 10), () {
   _messageCtrl.clear();
});
```

